---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import RelatedLinks from "../components/RelatedLinks.astro";
---

<Base
  title="Medical Cannabis — Mary Jane's Place"
  description="A clear, honest overview of medical cannabis in the UK: what it is, who can be prescribed it, how it is used, and the law that governs it."
>
  <section class="ph-top pad">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <div class="eyebrow kick rv">Medical Cannabis</div>
      <h1 class="rv">Medical cannabis, explained.</h1>
      <p class="rv lede" style="margin-top:16px">
        A clear, honest overview of what medical cannabis is in the UK, who can be
        prescribed it, and how patients use it. This is general information, not medical advice.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="pad-sm" style="padding-top:0">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="info">
        <div class="info-block rv">
          <h3>What it is</h3>
          <p>
            Cannabis-based products for medicinal use (CBPMs) are pharmaceutical-grade
            medicines — flower, oils or capsules — manufactured to a consistent, tested
            standard. Since November 2018 they have been Schedule 2 controlled drugs that
            specialist doctors can lawfully prescribe.
            <span class="src">Misuse of Drugs (Amendments) Regulations 2018</span>
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-block rv">
          <h3>Who can be prescribed it</h3>
          <p>
            Typically adults with a diagnosed condition who have tried at least two
            other treatments without adequate relief. Only a GMC-registered specialist can
            initiate a prescription — GPs cannot — and most prescriptions are private. No GP
            referral is needed to approach a clinic.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-block rv">
          <h3>THC, CBD &amp; the endocannabinoid system</h3>
          <p>
            THC is the psychoactive cannabinoid that helps with pain, nausea and muscle
            relaxation; CBD is non-psychoactive, with calming and anti-inflammatory
            properties. Both work via the body's endocannabinoid system. Most prescriptions
            blend the two to suit the patient.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-block rv">
          <h3>How it's taken</h3>
          <p>
            Patients use a dry-herb vaporiser, which gently heats the flower rather than
            burning it, or take oils and capsules. <b style="color:var(--ink)">Smoking remains
            prohibited even with a prescription</b> — which is exactly why a vaporiser-only
            space like ours is appropriate and lawful.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-block rv">
          <h3>Dosing</h3>
          <p>
            The guiding principle is "start low, go slow." Patients titrate to the lowest
            effective dose under their prescriber's guidance. Our team can help you
            understand a device, but dosing decisions always sit with you and your clinician.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-block rv">
          <h3>Conditions commonly treated</h3>
          <p>
            There is no fixed list — a specialist may prescribe wherever the clinical
            evidence supports it. Common areas include chronic pain, anxiety, PTSD,
            MS-related spasticity, chemotherapy-induced nausea, and treatment-resistant
            epilepsy.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Getting started: unbiased clinic + device guidance -->
  <section class="pad-sm" style="padding-top:0">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="eyebrow kick rv">Getting a prescription</div>
      <h2 class="rv" style="margin-bottom:8px">Not sure where to start?</h2>
      <p class="rv" style="max-width:66ch;margin-bottom:22px">
        We're not doctors and we don't prescribe. But if you think medical cannabis might
        help and don't know where to begin, just ask — we'll point you in the right direction.
      </p>
      <div class="two">
        <div class="rv card" style="background:var(--paper);border-left:4px solid var(--olive)">
          <div class="eyebrow">Finding a clinic</div>
          <h3 style="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:10px">Independent, no bias</h3>
          <p>
            We can guide you to UK specialist clinics so you can book your own assessment —
            no GP referral needed. We take no commission and have no tie-ins, so we won't push
            one clinic over another. We'll share the options; the choice is yours.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rv card" style="background:var(--paper);border-left:4px solid var(--olive)">
          <div class="eyebrow">Choosing a device</div>
          <h3 style="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:10px">Honest, not pushed</h3>
          <p>
            Same with equipment. We'll tell you straight what suits your needs and budget —
            not whatever earns us the most. Try one in the lounge before you buy, and ask us
            anything.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="rv" style="margin-top:20px;display:flex;gap:10px;flex-wrap:wrap">
        <a class="btn" href="/contact">Ask us about clinics <span class="arr">→</span></a>
        <a class="btn ghost" href="/shop">Browse devices</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="pad-sm" style="padding-top:0">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <div class="eyebrow kick rv">Administration methods</div>
      <p class="rv lede" style="margin-top:14px">
        Prescribed cannabis-based medicines come in several forms. Which one suits a
        patient is a clinical decision, made with the prescriber.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="wrap" style="margin-top:22px">
      <div class="info">
        <div class="info-block rv">
          <h3>Vapour (dried flower)</h3>
          <p>
            Dried flower is used in a dry-herb vaporiser, which gently heats the flower to
            release its cannabinoids as vapour rather than burning it. It is usually
            prescribed as named flower cultivars in sealed, labelled containers, with the
            THC and CBD content stated.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-block rv">
          <h3>Oils &amp; tinctures</h3>
          <p>
            Cannabis oils and tinctures are liquid preparations taken under the tongue with
            a dropper or oral syringe. In the UK they are dispensed in measured bottles with
            a defined cannabinoid concentration, which makes consistent, gradual dosing
            straightforward.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-block rv">
          <h3>Capsules</h3>
          <p>
            Capsules contain a fixed, pre-measured dose of cannabis extract and are
            swallowed like any other oral medicine. They are dispensed as standard
            pharmacy packs, offering a familiar, discreet format with predictable dosing.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-block rv">
          <h3>Edibles</h3>
          <p>
            Edibles are cannabis medicines formulated to be eaten, such as pastilles. Like
            oils and capsules, they are taken orally, so effects build more slowly and last
            longer than inhaled vapour. They are dispensed as labelled, dose-controlled
            products on prescription.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="rv" style="margin-top:18px;font-size:14.5px;color:var(--ink-soft)">
        Of these, only vapour administration is available on the premises — a dry-herb
        vaporiser is the mechanism our space is built around.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="pad-sm">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <div class="eyebrow kick rv">Strain types</div>
      <p class="rv lede" style="margin-top:14px">
        Flower is often described by strain type. These are broad characterisations rather
        than precise rules, and a patient's response is individual.
      </p>
      <ul class="checks rv" style="margin-top:18px">
        <li><b style="color:var(--ink)">Indica</b> — traditionally associated with more relaxing, body-centred effects.</li>
        <li><b style="color:var(--ink)">Sativa</b> — traditionally associated with more uplifting, daytime effects.</li>
        <li><b style="color:var(--ink)">Hybrid</b> — a cross of the two, blending characteristics in varying proportions.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="rv" style="margin-top:16px;color:var(--ink-soft)">
        Whichever the format or strain type, these products are dispensed in the UK only
        through prescriptions issued by a registered specialist clinician.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="pad-sm">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <div class="eyebrow kick rv">Common questions</div>
      <div class="acc rv" style="margin-top:14px;border-top:1px solid var(--line)">
        <details class="acc-item">
          <summary>Is medical cannabis the same as street cannabis?</summary>
          <div>
            No. Prescribed CBPMs are manufactured to Good Manufacturing Practice (GMP)
            standards — tested for contaminants, with consistent labelled cannabinoid
            content and full batch traceability. Unregulated cannabis has none of these
            safeguards.
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="acc-item">
          <summary>How do I become a patient?</summary>
          <div>
            You can approach a specialist medical cannabis clinic directly, without a GP
            referral. They will assess your eligibility and, if appropriate, a specialist
            will prescribe. Access schemes exist for some patients on low incomes, veterans
            and students.
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="acc-item">
          <summary>Why vaporising and not smoking?</summary>
          <div>
            Smoking cannabis is prohibited by the legislation even with a prescription,
            because the issue is combustion. A vaporiser heats the flower without burning
            it, producing vapour rather than smoke — and falls outside the smoke-free law.
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="acc-item">
          <summary>Do you sell or supply cannabis?</summary>
          <div>
            No, and we never will. We are not a dispensary. Patients bring their own
            prescribed medicine; we provide the space, the equipment to use it, and
            the information.
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
      <div class="disc rv" style="margin-top:24px">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="9"/><path d="M12 8v5M12 16h.01"/></svg>
        <div>
          This page is general information drawn from public UK sources and patient
          organisations. It is <b>not medical advice</b>. Whether medical cannabis is right
          for you is a decision for a qualified specialist. For your legal rights, see
          <a class="tlink" href="/your-rights">Your Rights</a>.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="pad-sm" style="padding-top:0">
    <div class="wrap">
      <RelatedLinks items={[
        { href: "/your-rights", label: "Your rights" },
        { href: "/membership", label: "Become a member" },
        { href: "/visit", label: "Visit us" },
        { href: "/for-police-and-venues", label: "For police & venues" },
      ]} />
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .acc-item { border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line); }
  .acc-item summary {
    list-style: none; cursor: pointer; padding: 19px 2px;
    display: flex; justify-content: space-between; gap: 16px; align-items: center;
    font-family: var(--font); font-size: 18px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--olive-d);
  }
  .acc-item summary::-webkit-details-marker { display: none; }
  .acc-item summary::after {
    content: "+"; flex: none; width: 24px; height: 24px; border-radius: 6px;
    border: 1.5px solid var(--line); display: grid; place-items: center;
    transition: 0.25s; font-size: 17px; color: var(--olive); line-height: 1;
  }
  .acc-item[open] summary::after {
    background: var(--olive); border-color: var(--olive); color: #fff; transform: rotate(45deg);
  }
  .acc-item > div { padding: 0 2px 20px; color: var(--ink-soft); font-size: 16px; max-width: 74ch; }
</style>
